# swiftui Best Practices

SwiftUI is a powerful framework for building user interfaces on Apple platforms. This guide outlines the best practices to follow, ensuring your applications are performant, maintainable, and scalable.

## Code Organization and Structure

### Use Separate Types for Views
Define views as separate types instead of computed properties to create isolated invalidation boundaries. This improves performance by reducing unnecessary re-renders.

❌ BAD
```swift
struct ContentView: View {
    var body: some View {
        VStack {
            Text("Hello, World!")
            // More complex views
        }
    }
}
```

✅ GOOD
```swift
struct ContentView: View {
    var body: some View {
        MainVStack()
    }
}

struct MainVStack: View {
    var body: some View {
        VStack {
            Text("Hello, World!")
            // More complex views
        }
    }
}
```

### Use the Repository Pattern
Isolate data logic from ViewModels by adopting the repository pattern. This enhances testability and separation of concerns.

✅ GOOD
```swift
protocol UserRepository {
    func fetchUsers() -> [User]
}

class UserViewModel: ObservableObject {
    private let repository: UserRepository

    @Published var users: [User] = []

    init(repository: UserRepository) {
        self.repository = repository
        loadUsers()
    }

    private func loadUsers() {
        users = repository.fetchUsers()
    }
}
```

## Common Patterns and Anti-patterns

### Use @Observable for Property-Level Re-rendering
Utilize the `@Observable` macro to enable more granular updates, enhancing performance.

❌ BAD
```swift
class UserModel: ObservableObject {
    @Published var name: String = ""
    @Published var age: Int = 0
}
```

✅ GOOD
```swift
struct UserModel {
    @Observable var name: String = ""
    @Observable var age: Int = 0
}
```

### Avoid Array Indices for Identifiers
Preserve view identity by using `Identifiable` instead of relying on array indices.

❌ BAD
```swift
struct UserListView: View {
    var users: [User]

    var body: some View {
        List(users.indices, id: \.self) { index in
            Text(users[index].name)
        }
    }
}
```

✅ GOOD
```swift
struct UserListView: View {
    var users: [User]

    var body: some View {
        List(users) { user in
            Text(user.name)
        }
    }
}
```

## Performance Considerations

### Keep Body Logic Declarative
Minimize complex operations within the `body` property to maintain clarity and performance.

❌ BAD
```swift
var body: some View {
    if isLoading {
        ProgressView()
    } else {
        Text(data)
    }
}
```

✅ GOOD
```swift
var body: some View {
    Group {
        if isLoading {
            ProgressView()
        } else {
            Text(data)
        }
    }
}
```

## Common Pitfalls and Gotchas

### Avoid Using if/else for State Changes
Use ternary operators for single-view state changes to prevent unnecessary structural identity shifts.

❌ BAD
```swift
var body: some View {
    if isActive {
        Text("Active")
    } else {
        Text("Inactive")
    }
}
```

✅ GOOD
```swift
var body: some View {
    Text(isActive ? "Active" : "Inactive")
}
```

## Component Architecture

### Use NavigationStack with Typed Navigation Paths
For scalable and testable routing, prefer `NavigationStack` with typed paths.

✅ GOOD
```swift
struct AppNavigation: View {
    var body: some View {
        NavigationStack {
            MainView()
        }
    }
}

struct MainView: View {
    var body: some View {
        NavigationLink("Go to Detail", value: DetailPath())
    }
}
```

## Accessibility

### Ensure Accessibility Features are Enabled
Always use accessibility modifiers to enhance usability for all users.

✅ GOOD
```swift
Text("Welcome")
    .accessibilityLabel("Welcome message")
    .accessibilityHint("Tap to continue")
```

## Theming

### Use Environment for Dependency Injection
Inject dependencies via `@Environment` instead of singletons to improve testability.

✅ GOOD
```swift
struct ThemedView: View {
    @Environment(\.theme) var theme

    var body: some View {
        Text("Themed Text")
            .foregroundColor(theme.textColor)
    }
}
```

## Testing Approaches

### Write Unit Tests for ViewModels
Ensure that your ViewModels are thoroughly tested, especially when they contain business logic.

✅ GOOD
```swift
func testUserViewModel() {
    let mockRepository = MockUserRepository()
    let viewModel = UserViewModel(repository: mockRepository)

    viewModel.loadUsers()
    XCTAssertEqual(viewModel.users.count, expectedCount)
}
```

By following these best practices, you'll ensure that your SwiftUI applications are not only performant but also maintainable and scalable. Embrace these patterns to enhance your development experience and deliver high-quality applications.